---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Who Pays to Park? Mapping Tel Aviv's Parking Equity by Neighborhood"
  year="2023"
  category="Urban Policy Analysis · Cartography"
  tools={['Python', 'GeoPandas', 'QGIS', 'Choropleth Mapping', 'Spatial Join']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Background</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Tel Aviv's curbside parking splits into paid (blue-and-white), free (white-line) and newly
        introduced grey regulated zones — and the rollout of paid parking is politically sensitive,
        since who absorbs the cost tracks closely with neighborhood demographics and distance from
        the center. This project mapped that distribution to answer a policy question directly: is
        the burden of paid parking falling evenly across the city?
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Maps — Parking Type by Neighborhood</h2>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/parking-blue-white.png`}
      alt="Choropleth map showing percentage of blue-and-white paid parking by Tel Aviv neighborhood"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Share of blue-and-white (paid) parking spaces by neighborhood. Darker shading indicates higher
      proportion of paid curbside.
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/parking-free-neighborhood.png`}
      alt="Choropleth map showing percentage of free parking by Tel Aviv neighborhood"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Share of free (unpaid) parking by neighborhood — the inverse of the paid parking distribution,
      highlighting which areas retain the most free curbside access.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methodology</h2>
    <ul class="proj-list">
      <li>Spatially joined the municipal parking-space inventory to neighborhood boundaries with <strong>GeoPandas</strong>, computing the share of paid vs. free spaces per neighborhood.</li>
      <li>Built <strong>choropleth maps</strong> in <strong>QGIS</strong> using <strong>Jenks natural-breaks classification</strong> for technical review, plus simplified manual-break versions for committee presentations.</li>
      <li>Tested multiple color palettes for perceptual clarity, validating the final selections for color-vision-deficiency accessibility.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Results</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        The pattern was stark: central neighborhoods are overwhelmingly paid, while peripheral areas
        retain large shares of free curbside access. That spatial portrait now underpins ongoing
        committee discussions about the pace and geography of the next phase of paid-parking rollout.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>

<style>
  :global(.proj-list) {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
    max-width: 68ch;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li) {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: #2A2A2A;
    padding-left: 1.2em;
    position: relative;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li::before) {
    content: '—';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: #3D5E35;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
</style>
